  <div class="article-content">
    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
  <p>Evelyn Scott's inversion is not a patient anecdote. It is a diagnostic error — one committed by multiple clinicians, across multiple years, in a pattern now documented across 63 countries. "Clinicians said, you are having painful periods because you are depressed," she told Think Global Health in 2025. "And I was like, no, no, no, I'm depressed because I'm having painful periods and I can't cope with it." The causality was reversed in the medical record. The correct mechanism was sitting in her body, measurable, biological, and entirely ignored.</p>
  <p>While those clinicians were writing "anxiety" in her notes, here is what was actually happening in her brain: macrophages recruited to endometriotic lesions were secreting interleukin-1β and tumor necrosis factor-alpha. Those cytokines were sensitizing peripheral nociceptors. Repeated nociceptive signaling was inducing glial activation — microglial and astrocytic — in the thalamus, hippocampus, and prefrontal cortex. These are not incidental structures. They are the brain's emotional regulation architecture. And they were, in the precise clinical sense of the word, inflamed. A 2025 investigation published in the Journal of Clinical Medicine confirmed this sequence in murine models: repeated endometriotic lesion induction produced sustained neuroinflammation in exactly these regions, with elevated IL-1β and TNF-α as the measurable signature. Scott's clinicians were not treating a psychiatric condition. They were misreading a neuroinflammatory one.</p>
  <p>This distinction — between a brain reacting to a disease and a brain generating a psychiatric disorder — is the difference between a decade of a woman's life. The average diagnostic delay for endometriosis is 9.6 years, documented in a 2023 international study of more than 2,000 women across 63 countries. That number is not a systemic inefficiency. It is the duration of a closed loop that medicine built and medicine sustains.</p>
</section>

<section id="the-biology-not-the-biography" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Biology, Not the Biography</h2>
  <p>Endometriosis affects an estimated 190 million women worldwide, according to the World Health Organization. It is estrogen-dependent, chronic, and systemic — though that last word has only recently begun appearing in the clinical literature with any seriousness. A 2024 editorial in <em>Clinics</em> called explicitly for the disease to be redefined as systemic rather than pelvic, citing psychiatric comorbidities so widespread that they constitute a parallel disease burden. Amanda Della Giustina, clinical research associate at the Ottawa Hospital Research Institute, put it plainly in 2024: "It is time for the health-care and scientific communities to recognize endometriosis no longer as a pelvic, but rather a systemic condition."</p>
  <p>The psychiatric burden is not subtle. A matched cohort study published in the <em>American Journal of Obstetrics and Gynecology</em> in 2024 — Thiel et al., drawing on Ontario population data — found that 67% of endometriosis patients were diagnosed with a mental health condition, compared to 51.2% of matched controls. Incidence rates were 105.3 versus 66.5 events per 1,000 person-years. A 2025 meta-analysis in the <em>Archives of Medical Science</em>, synthesizing data from multiple cohorts, found women with endometriosis had 1.89 times the risk of depression and 1.82 times the risk of anxiety compared to the general population. In one cohort, 44.3% had depressive symptoms, 25.3% had anxiety, and 31.7% had elevated stress. The same analysis identified a 44.7% higher risk of suicide. A separate cohort reported a 231.5% higher risk of all-cause mortality.</p>
  <p>These are not quality-of-life footnotes. They are a public health failure with a body count.</p>
  <p>The question the research has been slow to ask — and slower to answer — is mechanistic. Not whether emotional dysregulation occurs in endometriosis, but why, and through what specific biological pathways. The answer, assembled from converging evidence across immunology, neuroendocrinology, and pain science, involves at least three distinct and mutually reinforcing mechanisms. None of them are metaphors.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"While clinicians were writing 'anxiety' in her notes, macrophages were secreting IL-1β and TNF-α into the structures that govern emotional regulation. The brain was inflamed. The diagnosis was wrong."</p></aside>

<section id="three-mechanisms" class="reveal">
  <h2>Three Mechanisms Medicine Has Not Connected</h2>
  <p><strong>First: estrogen-mediated limbic dysregulation.</strong> Endometriosis is driven by pathologically elevated estrogen production — a consistent endocrine characteristic of endometriotic lesions, documented in a 2024 review in <em>Frontiers in Medicine</em> examining the immunological and physiological links between endometriosis and depression. Estrogen does not stay in the pelvis. It crosses the blood-brain barrier and modulates limbic system activity directly. Elevated estrogen lowers the threshold for irritability, mood instability, and anger by acting on estrogen receptors in the amygdala and hypothalamus — structures that regulate threat detection and emotional reactivity. This is not a side effect. It is a pharmacological action of the disease's primary driver, operating on the brain's emotional circuitry.</p>
  <p><strong>Second: the neuroinflammatory cascade.</strong> Endometriotic lesions recruit macrophages that secrete proinflammatory cytokines — IL-1β, IL-6, TNF-α — and nerve growth factor. These molecules sensitize peripheral nociceptors, generating a sustained pain signal. Repeated nociceptive input induces central sensitization: glial cells in the thalamus, hippocampus, and prefrontal cortex activate, releasing further inflammatory mediators and altering synaptic transmission in regions governing emotional regulation and threat response. The 2025 murine study in the <em>Journal of Clinical Medicine</em> confirmed this sequence directly, demonstrating that repeated lesion induction produces microglial and astrocytic activation in these specific brain regions, with elevated IL-1β and TNF-α as the measurable output. This neuroinflammatory profile is not unique to endometriosis — it mirrors the brain changes documented in chronic stress disorders and PTSD. The emotional consequences are not analogous to those conditions. They are produced by the same cellular machinery.</p>
  <p><strong>Third: HPA axis and neuroendocrine disruption.</strong> The hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal axis — the body's primary stress-response system — is dysregulated in endometriosis through multiple routes. Elevated prolactin, disrupted cortisol signaling, and dopamine receptor polymorphisms collectively impair emotional homeostasis. Dysregulated cortisol blunts the normal stress-recovery response, leaving the nervous system in a state of sustained activation. Dopamine pathway disruption affects reward processing and impulse regulation. These are not secondary complications. They are direct neuroendocrine outputs of a disease that has been classified, treated, and researched almost exclusively as a gynecological one.</p>
  <p>A 2022 study from the National Institute of Perinatology in Mexico City, published in PMC, added a further precision: it is not just pain severity but pain chronicity that drives emotional dysregulation. Women with non-cyclical, persistent chronic pelvic pain showed significantly higher emotional dysregulation than those with cyclical pain. The brain adapts — badly — to unrelenting input. Anger, in this context, is not a personality trait. It is a neurological adaptation to sustained inflammatory assault.</p>
</section>

<div class="info-card my-12 reveal">
  <h4 class="font-serif text-lg font-semibold mb-3 text-primary-700 dark:text-primary-400">The Triple-Mechanism Architecture</h4>
  <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm">
    <li><strong>Estrogen-mediated limbic dysregulation:</strong> Pathologically elevated estrogen modulates amygdala and hypothalamic activity, directly lowering the threshold for irritability and anger.</li>
    <li><strong>Neuroinflammatory cascade:</strong> Lesion-recruited macrophages secrete IL-1β, IL-6, and TNF-α, sensitizing peripheral nociceptors and inducing glial activation in the thalamus, hippocampus, and prefrontal cortex — the brain's emotional regulation core.</li>
    <li><strong>HPA axis disruption:</strong> Elevated prolactin, dysregulated cortisol, and dopamine receptor polymorphisms impair emotional homeostasis through the neuroendocrine-immune axis.</li>
    <li><strong>Chronicity amplifier:</strong> Non-cyclical persistent pain produces significantly greater emotional dysregulation than cyclical pain, independent of severity (National Institute of Perinatology, 2022).</li>
    <li><strong>Diagnostic delay multiplier:</strong> Average 9.6-year delay across 63 countries compounds neuroinflammatory burden and generates a parallel psychosocial trauma layer.</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<section id="the-double-bind" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Double Bind Medicine Built</h2>
  <p>Here is the loop. The disease generates anger neurobiologically. The patient presents to a clinician with pelvic pain and emotional dysregulation. The clinician — trained in a system that has not updated its endometriosis framework to include neuropsychiatric outputs — interprets the anger as evidence of psychiatric instability. The psychiatric label delays correct diagnosis. The delay extends the neuroinflammatory exposure. The neuroinflammatory exposure intensifies the emotional dysregulation. The intensified dysregulation confirms the clinician's original read. Repeat for 9.6 years.</p>
  <p>Nearly half of U.S. endometriosis patients reported that healthcare providers initially attributed their physical symptoms to mental health issues before a correct diagnosis was made. This is not a fringe experience. A Manchester Metropolitan University study published in the <em>Journal of Health Communication</em> in 2024, examining 33 women through the COM-B behavioral framework, found that "medical gaslighting" was viewed by participants as systemic within healthcare — not as individual clinician failure — and that it directly generated fear, anger, frustration, depression, and anxiety, while eroding confidence in seeking further help. The emotional response to medical dismissal is not irrational. It is the appropriate output of a nervous system that has been repeatedly told its signals are wrong.</p>
  <p>A 2025 systematic review from Rutgers University's Robert Wood Johnson Medical School, led by Allyson Bontempo, PhD, analyzed 151 qualitative reports representing 11,307 individuals — 81% female — with conditions including endometriosis. It identified four distinct harm categories from symptom invalidation. One of them was named with clinical precision: "healthcare-specific emotional states" — a cluster comprising frustration, anger, and loss of trust in medical practitioners. Bontempo noted that patients can begin to "question reality" under sustained invalidation. That is not a metaphor for confusion. It is a description of induced epistemic destabilization — a system teaching a patient that her own perceptions are unreliable. The anger that follows is not a symptom of instability. It is evidence of a functioning threat-detection system responding to a genuine threat.</p>
  <p>The 9.6-year diagnostic delay documented across 63 countries is not a statistic about administrative inefficiency. It is the measured duration of this loop, averaged across a global population. Della Giustina noted in 2024 that "it's very common for physicians not to know the symptoms of endometriosis" — a statement that, in the context of 190 million affected women, constitutes a structural indictment of medical education, not a description of individual ignorance.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"The disease generates anger neurobiologically. The system interprets that anger as psychiatric instability. The psychiatric label delays diagnosis. The delay extends neuroinflammatory exposure. The exposure intensifies the anger. This is a closed loop that medicine built."</p></aside>

<section id="what-the-evidence-actually-says" class="reveal">
  <h2>What the Evidence Actually Says — and Doesn't</h2>
  <p>The counter-argument deserves a direct hearing, because it is not wrong — it is incomplete. Anger and irritability in endometriosis patients may be primarily reactive: a rational psychological response to chronic pain, diagnostic delay, and repeated medical dismissal. This distinction matters for treatment. If the anger is purely reactive, addressing the disease and the healthcare failures may resolve it without separate psychiatric intervention. That is a legitimate clinical hypothesis.</p>
  <p>The problem is that "purely reactive" cannot be the correct framing when the biology is this specific. A 2024 meta-analysis in <em>Frontiers in Psychology</em>, examining seven RCTs with a combined sample of 757 patients, found that psychological interventions produced large reductions in trait anxiety (mean difference: -6.63) and depression (mean difference: -2.49), and likely reduced state anxiety (mean difference: -9.72). These are not trivial effect sizes. They suggest that emotional dysregulation in endometriosis is meaningfully modifiable through psychological care — which is consistent with both a reactive model and a neurobiological one, since neuroinflammation itself is partially responsive to stress-reduction interventions.</p>
  <p>The honest position, supported by the evidence, is that both mechanisms are true simultaneously and inseparably. The neuroinflammation is real. The gaslighting is real. They are mutually reinforcing, and the pain-mood relationship between them runs in both directions: a 2024 meta-analysis of 99,614 women from 24 studies, published in the <em>Archives of Medical Science</em>, identified pain as the primary mediating factor linking endometriosis to depression, while also acknowledging that depression amplifies pain perception through central sensitization. The causal arrow does not point in one direction. It points in a circle.</p>
  <p>What the research cannot yet do cleanly is isolate anger as a primary outcome variable. Most studies measure anxiety and depression using validated scales. Anger is rarely the primary endpoint. Confounding is significant: women with endometriosis frequently carry comorbid diagnoses — irritable bowel syndrome, fibromyalgia, interstitial cystitis — that independently contribute to mood disturbance. A 2024 systematic review in <em>Fertility and Sterility</em>, covering studies from 2003 to 2023, found depressive symptoms in 9.8% to 98.5% of endometriosis patients versus 6.6% to 9.3% of controls — a range so wide it reflects methodological heterogeneity as much as clinical reality. The same review noted emerging evidence of shared genetic predisposition between endometriosis and mental health disorders, suggesting the link is not purely reactive in origin.</p>
  <p>The argument here is not that the science is settled on anger specifically. It is that the converging evidence from neuroinflammation research, estrogen dysregulation studies, and pain chronicity data makes the biological mechanism highly plausible — and that medicine's failure to investigate it further, given the scale of the affected population and the severity of the documented harms, is itself a form of institutional neglect.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"Psychological interventions produce large effect sizes — trait anxiety MD: -6.63 across seven RCTs. They are almost never offered as part of standard endometriosis care. The disease is systemic. The treatment is still pelvic."</p></aside>

<section id="the-treatment-gap" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Treatment Gap Is Not an Oversight</h2>
  <p>The meta-analysis in <em>Frontiers in Psychology</em> — seven RCTs, 757 patients, large effect sizes across anxiety and depression outcomes — represents the clearest evidence that psychological intervention works in endometriosis. Trait anxiety reduction of 6.63 mean difference points is not a marginal finding. It is clinically significant. And it is almost never offered as part of standard endometriosis care.</p>
  <p>Standard care remains surgical and hormonal: laparoscopic excision, GnRH agonists, combined oral contraceptives. These address the pelvic lesions. They do not address the neuroinflammatory state those lesions have induced in the thalamus and hippocampus. They do not address the HPA axis dysregulation. They do not address the 9.6 years of compounding psychosocial trauma. A 2025 commentary in Think Global Health noted that health systems "fail to train doctors to spot" the psychiatric connections of endometriosis, and that "the widespread comorbidities of this disease require increased awareness among all medical specialties, not just gynecologists." That is a polite way of saying that the specialty boundary between gynecology and psychiatry has become a place where patients fall through.</p>
  <p>The scoping review published in <em>Gynecology</em> in 2024 found moderate-to-strong correlations between worse health-related quality of life and both depressive symptoms (r = -0.54) and anxiety symptoms (r = -0.60) in endometriosis patients. HRQoL scores were significantly worse in patients with any of six types of mental health symptoms compared to those without. The disease is systemic. The harm is systemic. The treatment protocol is not.</p>

<div class="info-card my-12 reveal">
  <h4 class="font-serif text-lg font-semibold mb-3 text-primary-700 dark:text-primary-400">Key Statistics: The Scale of Institutional Failure</h4>
  <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm">
    <li><strong>Global prevalence:</strong> 190 million women worldwide (WHO)</li>
    <li><strong>Mental health diagnosis rate:</strong> 67% of endometriosis patients vs. 51.2% of controls (Thiel et al., AJOG 2024)</li>
    <li><strong>Depression risk:</strong> 1.89x higher than general population (Archives of Medical Science, 2025)</li>
    <li><strong>Anxiety risk:</strong> 1.82x higher than general population (Archives of Medical Science, 2025)</li>
    <li><strong>Suicide risk elevation:</strong> 44.7% higher (Archives of Medical Science, 2025)</li>
    <li><strong>Average diagnostic delay:</strong> 9.6 years across 63 countries (2023 international study, N=2,000+)</li>
    <li><strong>Psychological intervention effect size:</strong> Trait anxiety MD -6.63 across 7 RCTs, N=757 (Frontiers in Psychology, 2024)</li>
    <li><strong>Symptom invalidation study scope:</strong> 151 qualitative reports, 11,307 individuals (Rutgers, 2025)</li>
  </ul>
</div>

  <p>Peter Saddington, a therapist with experience in chronic pain populations, described the anger plainly to the Endometriosis Foundation of America: "When you live with chronic pain, you can't predict how life will be, day-to-day. Ordinary things can be difficult. This can lead you to feel angry and depressed that life has affected you in this way." That is the reactive model, accurately described. What Saddington does not account for — and what the clinical literature has been slow to integrate — is that the anger is not only a response to unpredictability. It is a neurobiological output of the same inflammatory process generating the unpredictability. The emotion and the disease share a mechanism. Treating one without the other is not a treatment plan. It is a partial one.</p>
</section>

<section id="the-diagnostic-inversion" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Diagnostic Inversion</h2>
  <p>The system trained clinicians to see an angry woman with pelvic pain and think: psychiatric. The neuroscience now says: neuroinflammation. Those are not the same diagnosis, and the difference between them is not semantic. It is a decade of a woman's life, a 44.7% elevated suicide risk, and a treatment gap that psychological intervention evidence suggests is entirely closeable — if anyone bothered to close it.</p>
  <p>The most uncomfortable implication of this evidence is not that clinicians were unkind. Most were not. It is that the diagnostic framework they were given was wrong in a specific, correctable, and well-documented way — and that the framework has not been updated at the speed the evidence warrants. A 2024 review in <em>Fertility and Sterility</em> found depressive symptoms in endometriosis patients at rates up to 98.5% in some cohorts. The Thiel et al. cohort study found incidence rates of mental health diagnoses at 105.3 events per 1,000 person-years in endometriosis patients. These numbers have been in the literature. They have not changed clinical training in any systematic way.</p>
  <p>Evelyn Scott's inversion — "I'm depressed because I'm having painful periods" — is not a patient's intuition correcting a clinician's mistake. It is a patient accurately describing a neurobiological sequence that the clinical literature now supports and that the clinical system has not yet incorporated. The anger she felt in that consultation room was not a symptom of her psychology. It was a symptom of her thalamus, her hippocampus, her dysregulated HPA axis, and a macrophage-driven cytokine cascade that no one in that room had been trained to recognize.</p>
  <p>The evidence now requires clinicians to do one specific thing differently: when an endometriosis patient presents with anger, the first clinical question should not be "is this patient difficult?" It should be "what is her neuroinflammatory burden, and what is her access to psychological intervention?" That is not a radical reframe. It is what the data says. The only remaining question is whether medicine will read it.</p>
</section>

